basic privileges info:
  windows account groups relevant to priv esc:
    users: low-priv accounts, no access to anything outside of their own files
    administrators: used for system admin, control permissions over most objects
    service user accounts: built into windows and used by the service control manager (SCM) to run services that windows relies on
      LocalService: has minimum privileges, authenticates with anonymous creds
      NetworkService: has minimum privilges, authenticates with computer's creds
      LocalSystem: full control over most objects, highest level of access
  
  user rights assignment:
    logon rights: control how and where an account is allowed to log on to a computer
    user rights: control access to objects

  vulnerable services:
    services are a large attack surface bc they frequently run as SYSTEM
    we can then abuse this via:
      DLL search order hijacking
      path interception
      weak service file permissions
      weak service registry permissions
      generic software vulnerabilities
  NOTE: we can list these services in cobalt strike using 'sc_enum', stop a service using 
  sc_stop' and start using 'sc_start'

path interception:
  class of vulnerability where an adversary drops an exe in a location where it will execute before the intended one
  PATH env variable:
    if we modify this variable to include a directory writable by our user we can drop our malicious exe
    NOTE: we can inspect this variable by running 'env'
  search order hijacking:
    if we have write permissions to the directory from the binary is running we may be able to overwrite other exes (e.g. cmd.exe)
  unquoted paths:
     while enumerating services, if we see any with an unquoted path we can check if any directories are writable
     if so, we can upload an exe with the necessary name to get executed
     NOTE: we will have to start and stop the service to have it trigger

weak service permissions:
  service file permissions: 
    we may be able to overwrite a service entirely
    NOTE: we will have to stop the service, then upload our payload, then start again
  service registry permissions:
    we may be able to modify a service's registry config to point to a different binary
      e.g. sc_config BadWindowsService C:\Path\to\Payload.exe 0 2

dll search order hijacking:
  this occurs when we are able to write a malicious DLL into a directory that is higher in the search order than the intended DLL

